it's good to practice these things
which we're gonna do in a little bit.

25
00:01:17.067 --> 00:01:21.539
But really kind of get the nerves out life
code it's really helpful to kind of see

26
00:01:21.539 --> 00:01:25.434
how someone works through a problem
when I'm giving a phone screen.

27
00:01:25.434 --> 00:01:31.918
As the candidate for phone screen, when
you're in the middle of it ask questions.

28
00:01:31.918 --> 00:01:35.216
I really want someone to ask me
questions like hey, can I do this?

29
00:01:35.216 --> 00:01:36.151
Should I do this?

30
00:01:36.151 --> 00:01:37.670
Is this the right way?

31
00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:42.480
Not too many questions for it's like well
now I'm just solving the problem for you.

32
00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.729
But I want someone to ask me questions
cuz that's how it is in real life.

33
00:01:45.729 --> 00:01:49.451
No one assigns your projects and
like good luck see you in a month.

34
00:01:49.451 --> 00:01:52.660
No, you have the dialogue and
that's what I want it with the coterie and

35
00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:55.568
that's what you should try to
establish with the interviewer.

36
00:01:55.568 --> 00:01:56.891
Are they helpful?

37
00:01:56.891 --> 00:01:58.906
Or are they dismissive.

38
00:01:58.906 --> 00:02:02.149
Are they friendly and outgoing, you're
like, I understand, phone screens suck,

39
00:02:02.149 --> 00:02:02.878
interviews suck.

40
00:02:02.878 --> 00:02:07.232
And they're friendly, or there always
like, this is a waste of my time,

41
00:02:07.232 --> 00:02:09.283
I can't believe I'm doing this.

42
00:02:09.283 --> 00:02:12.775
Why, doesn't this person
understand what I'm talking about?

43
00:02:12.775 --> 00:02:16.057
These are things you should vet out during
the phone screen, so ask questions.

44
00:02:16.057 --> 00:02:19.715
Talk out your solution,
especially if you get stuck.

45
00:02:19.715 --> 00:02:20.960
It does not help anybody.

46
00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:22.787
If you're sitting there
thinking inside your head.

47
00:02:22.787 --> 00:02:25.410
You have to talk out
loud in any interview.

48
00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:28.491
That's what you have to do you
want to establish here's how I'm

49
00:02:28.491 --> 00:02:29.816
thinking about a problem.

50
00:02:29.816 --> 00:02:34.360
And you might be absolutely right
the interview say yeah, good thinking.

51
00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:36.712
Yeah, no,
I think you're on the right path here or

52
00:02:36.712 --> 00:02:38.698
they might be like you're way off course.

53
00:02:38.698 --> 00:02:40.548
And the way you're thinking about
the problem is completely wrong.

54
00:02:40.548 --> 00:02:42.419
And here's a better way to think about it.

55
00:02:42.419 --> 00:02:46.091
But either way, you can't get
there unless you talk out loud and

56
00:02:46.091 --> 00:02:49.099
talk about how you're
thinking about the problem.

57
00:02:49.099 --> 00:02:51.319
And get comfortable in the environment.

58
00:02:51.319 --> 00:02:56.611
If using code pen or code tests,
there's a lot of them.

59
00:02:56.611 --> 00:02:57.285
Ask ahead of time,

60
00:02:57.285 --> 00:03:00.082
they'll generally send you a link to
the environment you're gonna be using.

61
00:03:00.082 --> 00:03:01.825
They'll say it's a CodePen link,
or something like that.

62
00:03:01.825 --> 00:03:04.603
Get comfortable,
understand the debugging scenario there.

63
00:03:04.603 --> 00:03:06.361
Some environments, you can debug.

64
00:03:06.361 --> 00:03:08.467
Some environments,
it's challenging to debug.

65
00:03:08.467 --> 00:03:11.075
But understand that,
are you gonna be running the code live?

66
00:03:11.075 --> 00:03:13.933
